# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: protein-expression-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Affinity chromatography has the advantage of specific binding interactions between the analyte of interest (normally dissolved in the mobile phase), and a binding partner or ligand (immobilized on the stationary phase).
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] In a typical affinity chromatography experiment, the ligand is attached to a solid, insoluble matrix—usually a polymer such as agarose or polyacrylamide—chemically modified to introduce reactive functional groups with which the ligand can react, forming stable covalent bonds.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The stationary phase is first loaded into a column to which the mobile phase is introduced.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Molecules that bind to the ligand will remain associated with the stationary phase.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] A wash buffer is then applied to remove non-target biomolecules by disrupting their weaker interactions with the stationary phase, while the biomolecules of interest will remain bound.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Target biomolecules may then be removed by applying a so-called elution buffer, which disrupts interactions between the bound target biomolecules and the ligand.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The target molecule is thus recovered in the eluting solution.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Affinity chromatography does not require the molecular weight, charge, hydrophobicity, or other physical properties of the analyte of interest to be known, although knowledge of its binding properties is useful in the design of a separation protocol.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Types of binding interactions commonly exploited in affinity chromatography procedures are summarized in the table below.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Binding to the solid phase may be achieved by column chromatography whereby the solid medium is packed onto a column, the initial mixture run through the column to allow settling, a wash buffer run through the column and the elution buffer subsequently applied to the column and collected.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] These steps are usually done at ambient pressure.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Alternatively, binding may be achieved using a batch treatment, for example, by adding the initial mixture to the solid phase in a vessel, mixing, separating the solid phase, removing the liquid phase, washing, re-centrifuging, adding the elution buffer, re-centrifuging and removing the elute.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Sometimes a hybrid method is employed such that the binding is done by the batch method, but the solid phase with the target molecule bound is packed onto a column and washing and elution are done on the column.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The ligands used in affinity chromatography are obtained from both organic and inorganic sources.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Examples of biological sources are serum proteins, lectins and antibodies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Inorganic sources are moronic acid, metal chelates and triazine dyes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] A third method, expanded bed absorption, which combines the advantages of the two methods mentioned above, has also been developed.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The solid phase particles are placed in a column where liquid phase is pumped in from the bottom and exits at the top.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The gravity of the particles ensure that the solid phase does not exit the column with the liquid phase.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Affinity columns can be eluted by changing salt concentrations, pH, pI, charge and ionic strength directly or through a gradient to resolve the particles of interest.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] More recently, setups employing more than one column in series have been developed.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The advantage compared to single column setups is that the resin material can be fully loaded since non-binding product is directly passed on to a consecutive column with fresh column material.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] These chromatographic processes are known as periodic counter-current chromatography (PCC).
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The resin costs per amount of produced product can thus be drastically reduced.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Since one column can always be eluted and regenerated while the other column is loaded, already two columns are sufficient to make full use of the advantages.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Additional columns can give additional flexibility for elution and regeneration times, at the cost of additional equipment and resin costs.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Affinity chromatography can be used in a number of applications, including nucleic acid purification, protein purification from cell free extracts, and purification from blood.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] By using affinity chromatography, one can separate proteins that bind to a certain fragment from proteins that do not bind that specific fragment.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Because this technique of purification relies on the biological properties of the protein needed, it is a useful technique and proteins can be purified many folds in one step.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Many different affinity media exist for a variety of possible uses.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Briefly, they are (generalized) activated/functionalized that work as a functional spacer, support matrix, and eliminates handling of toxic reagents.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Amino acid media is used with a variety of serum proteins, proteins, peptides, and enzymes, as well as rRNA and dsDNA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Avidin biotin media is used in the purification process of biotin/avidin and their derivatives.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Carbohydrate bonding is most often used with glycoproteins or any other carbohydrate-containing substance; carbohydrate is used with lectins, glycoproteins, or any other carbohydrate metabolite protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Dye ligand media is nonspecific but mimics biological substrates and proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Glutathione is useful for separation of GST tagged recombinant proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Hydrophobic interaction media are most commonly used to target free carboxyl groups and proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Nucleic acids function to trap mRNA, DNA, rRNA, and other nucleic acids/oligonucleotides.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Protein A/G method is used to purify immunoglobulins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Speciality media are designed for a specific class or type of protein/co enzyme; this type of media will only work to separate a specific protein or coenzyme.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Another use for the procedure is the affinity purification of antibodies from blood serum.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] If the serum is known to contain antibodies against a specific antigen (for example if the serum comes from an organism immunized against the antigen concerned) then it can be used for the affinity purification of that antigen.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] This is also known as Immunoaffinity Chromatography.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] For example, if an organism is immunised against a GST-fusion protein it will produce antibodies against the fusion-protein, and possibly antibodies against the GST tag as well.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The protein can then be covalently coupled to a solid support such as agarose and used as an affinity ligand in purifications of antibody from immune serum.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] For thoroughness, the GST protein and the GST-fusion protein can each be coupled separately.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The serum is initially allowed to bind to the GST affinity matrix.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] This will remove antibodies against the GST part of the fusion protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The serum is then separated from the solid support and allowed to bind to the GST-fusion protein matrix.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] This allows any antibodies that recognize the antigen to be captured on the solid support.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Elution of the antibodies of interest is most often achieved using a low pH buffer such as glycine pH 2.8.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The eluate is collected into a neutral tris or phosphate buffer, to neutralize the low pH elution buffer and halt any degradation of the antibody's activity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] This is a nice example as affinity purification is used to purify the initial GST-fusion protein, to remove the undesirable anti-GST antibodies from the serum and to purify the target antibody.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Monoclonal antibodies can also be selected to bind proteins with great specificity, where protein is released under fairly gentle conditions.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] This can become of use for further research in the future.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] A simplified strategy is often employed to purify antibodies generated against peptide antigens.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] When the peptide antigens are produced synthetically, a terminal cysteine residue is added at either the N- or C-terminus of the peptide.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] This cysteine residue contains a sulfhydryl functional group which allows the peptide to be easily conjugated to a carrier protein (e.g.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The same cysteine-containing peptide is also immobilized onto an agarose resin through the cysteine residue and is then used to purify the antibody.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Most monoclonal antibodies have been purified using affinity chromatography based on immunoglobulin-specific Protein A or Protein G, derived from bacteria.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Immunoaffinity chromatography with monoclonal antibodies immobilized on monolithic column has been successfully used to capture extracellular vesicles (e.g., exosomes and exomeres) from human blood plasma by targeting tetraspanins and integrins found on the surface of the EVs.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Immunoaffinity chromatography is also the basis for immunochromatographic test (ICT) strips, which provide a rapid means of diagnosis in patient care.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Using ICT, a technician can make a determination at a patient's bedside, without the need for a laboratory.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] ICT detection is highly specific to the microbe causing an infection.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Immunoaffinity chromatography has been applied to the selective isolation of blood-derived components, including lymphocytes and specific proteins, using antibody-functionalized stationary phases.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Antibody-based detection methods are also used in forensic serology to identify blood and evaluate its persistence on substrates over time, demonstrating the broader role of immunological specificity in forensic body-fluid analysis.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Immobilized metal ion affinity chromatography (IMAC) is based on the specific coordinate covalent bond of amino acids, particularly histidine, to metals.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Many naturally occurring proteins do not have an affinity for metal ions, therefore recombinant DNA technology can be used to introduce such a protein tag into the relevant gene.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Methods used to elute the protein of interest include changing the pH, or adding a competitive molecule, such as imidazole.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Possibly the most common use of affinity chromatography is for the purification of recombinant proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Proteins with a known affinity are protein tagged in order to aid their purification.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The protein may have been genetically modified so as to allow it to be selected for affinity binding; this is known as a fusion protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Protein tags include hexahistidine (His), glutathione-S-transferase (GST), maltose binding protein (MBP), and the Colicin E7 variant CL7 tag.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Histidine tags have an affinity for nickel, cobalt, zinc, copper and iron ions which have been immobilized by forming coordinate covalent bonds with a chelator incorporated in the stationary phase.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] For elution, an excess amount of a compound able to act as a metal ion ligand, such as imidazole, is used.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] GST has an affinity for glutathione which is commercially available immobilized as glutathione agarose.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] During elution, excess glutathione is used to displace the tagged protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] CL7 has an affinity and specificity for Immunity Protein 7 (Im7) which is commercially available immobilized as Im7 agarose resin.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] For elution, an active and site-specific protease is applied to the Im7 resin to release the tag-free protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Lectin affinity chromatography is a form of affinity chromatography where lectins are used to separate components within the sample.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Lectins, such as concanavalin A are proteins which can bind specific alpha-D-mannose and alpha-D-glucose carbohydrate molecules.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Some common carbohydrate molecules that is used in lectin affinity chromatography are Con A-Sepharose and WGA-agarose.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Another example of a lectin is wheat germ agglutinin which binds D-N-acetyl-glucosamine.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The most common application is to separate glycoproteins from non-glycosylated proteins, or one glycoform from another glycoform.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Although there are various ways to perform lectin affinity chromatography, the goal is extract a sugar ligand of the desired protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Another use for affinity chromatography is the purification of specific proteins using a gel matrix that is unique to a specific protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] This property allows the enzyme to bind to the stationary phase of the affinity matrix and β-Galactosidase is eluted by adding increasing concentrations of salt to the column.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Alkaline phosphatase from *E. coli* can be purified using a DEAE-Cellulose matrix.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] A. phosphatase has a slight negative charge, allowing it to weakly bind to the positively charged amine groups in the matrix.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The enzyme can then be eluted out by adding buffer with higher salt concentrations.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Boronate affinity chromatography consists of using boronic acid or boronates to elute and quantify amounts of glycoproteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Clinical adaptations have applied this type of chromatography for use in determining long term assessment of diabetic patients through analysis of their glycated hemoglobin.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Affinity purification of albumin and macroglobulin contamination is helpful in removing excess albumin and α2-macroglobulin contamination, when performing mass spectrometry.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] In affinity purification of serum albumin, the stationary used for collecting or attracting serum proteins can be Cibacron Blue-Sepharose.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Then the serum proteins can be eluted from the adsorbent with a buffer containing thiocyanate (SCN−).
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] The WAC technology is demonstrated against a number of different protein targets – proteases, kinases, chaperones and protein–protein interaction (PPI) targets.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] WAC has been shown to be more effective than established methods for fragment based screening.
[src:protein-expression-systems/affinity-chromatography] Affinity chromatography was conceived and first developed by Pedro Cuatrecasas and Meir Wilchek.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Baculoviruses are known to infect insects, with over 600 host species having been described.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Immature (larval) forms of lepidopteran species (moths and butterflies) are the most common hosts, but these viruses have also been found infecting sawflies, and mosquitoes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Although baculoviruses are capable of entering mammalian cells in culture, they are not known to be capable of replication in mammalian or other vertebrate animal cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Starting in the 1940s, they were used and studied widely as biopesticides in crop fields.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Baculoviruses contain a circular, double-stranded DNA (dsDNA) genome ranging from 80 to 180 kbp.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The earliest records of baculoviruses can be found in the literature from as early as the 16th century in reports of "wilting disease" infecting silkworm larvae.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Starting in the 1940s, the viruses were used and studied widely as biopesticides in crop fields.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Since the 1990s, they have been employed to produce complex eukaryotic proteins in insect cell cultures (see Sf21, High Five cells).
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] These recombinant proteins have been used in research and as vaccines in both human and veterinary medical treatments (for example, the most widely used vaccine for prevention of H5N1 avian influenza in chickens was produced in a baculovirus expression vector).
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] More recently, baculoviruses were found to transduce mammalian cells with a suitable promoter.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The baculovirus lifecycle involves two distinct forms of virus.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Occlusion-derived virus (ODV) is present in a protein matrix (polyhedrin or granulin) and is responsible for the primary infection of the host, while the budded virus (BV) is released from the infected host cells later during the secondary infection.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Baculoviruses have very species-specific tropisms among the invertebrates with over 700 host species having been described.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Immature (larval) forms of lepidopteran species are the most common hosts, but these viruses have also been found infecting sawflies and mosquitoes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Reports of baculovirus infections of shrimp and beetles (e.g.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] *Oryctes rhinocerus*) were found to be nudiviruses, a closely related lineage to the baculoviruses.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Typically, the initial infection occurs when a susceptible host insect feeds on plants that are contaminated with the occluded form of the virus.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The protein matrix dissolves in the alkaline environment of the host midgut (stomach), releasing ODVs that then fuse to the columnar epithelial cell membranes of the host intestine and are taken into the cell in endosomes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Nucleocapsids escape from the endosomes and are transported to nucleus.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] This step is possibly mediated by actin filaments.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Viral transcription and replication occur in the cell nucleus and new BV particles are budded out from the basolateral side to spread the infection systemically.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] During budding, BV acquires a loosely fitting host cell membrane with expressed and displayed viral glycoproteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] While BV is produced in the late phase, the ODV form is produced in the very late phase, acquiring the envelope from host cell nucleus and embedded in the matrix of occlusion body protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] These occlusion bodies are released when cells lyse to further spread baculovirus infection to next host.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The extensive lysis of cells frequently causes the host insect to literally disintegrate, thus the reason for the historic name "wilting disease".
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The complete ODV-polyhedrin particles are resistant to heat and light inactivation, whereas the naked BV virion is more sensitive to environment.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] When infecting a caterpillar, the advanced stages of infection cause the host to feed without resting, and then to climb to the higher parts of trees, including exposed places they would normally avoid due to the risk of predators.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] This is an advantage for the virus since (when the host dissolves) it can drip down onto leaves, which will be consumed by new hosts.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The virus is unable to infect humans in the way it does insects, because human stomachs are acid-based and NPV requires an alkaline digestive system in order to replicate.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] It is possible for the virus crystals to enter human cells, but not to replicate to the point of causing illness.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The most studied baculovirus is *Autographa californica multicapsid nucleopolyhedrovirus* (AcMNPV).
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The virus was originally isolated from the alfalfa looper (a lepidopteran) and contains a 134 kbp genome with 154 open reading frames.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The major capsid protein VP39 together with some minor proteins forms the nucleocapsid (21 nm x 260 nm) that encloses the DNA with p6.9 protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Using cryo–electron microscopy, it has been shown that the major capsid protein VP39 forms a covalently cross-linked helical tube protecting a highly compacted 134-kilobase pair DNA genome.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The ends of the tube are sealed by the base and cap substructures, which share a 126-subunit hub but differ in components that promote actin tail–mediated propulsion and nuclear entry of the nucleocapsid, respectively.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The fold of VP39 is novel and is unrelated to those of major capsid proteins encoded by non-baculo-like dsDNA viruses that belond to realms *Varidnaviria* and *Duplodnaviria*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The N terminus of VP39 contains a CCCH zinc finger motif with an unusual extension in the “knuckle” turn of the zinc finger containing the first two cysteines.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] This extension has a structural role as it projects away from the main body of the major capsid protein to form a interdimer disulfide bond between two Cys29 residues from neighboring VP39 strands in the nucleocapsid.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] BV acquires its envelope from the cell membrane and requires a glycoprotein, gp64, to be able to spread systemic infection.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] This protein forms structures called peplomers on one end of the budded virus particle, but is not found on ODVs (although several other proteins are only associated with the ODV form).
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Some differences also exist in the lipid composition of the viral envelope of the two forms.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] While the BV envelope consists of phosphatidylserine, ODV contains phosphatidylcholine and phosphatidylethanolamine.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] A nucleocapsid assembly-essential element (NAE) was identified in the AcMNPV genome.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The NAE is an internal *cis*-element within the *ac83* gene.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The nucleocapsid assembly is not dependent on the *ac83* protein product.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] During periods of evolution, the baculoviral envelope glycoproteins have undergone changes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Gp64 is a homotrimeric membrane glycoprotein that is polarly present on the rod-shaped virion.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] It consists of 512 amino acids (aa) with four glycosylation sites at asparagine residues and has a N-terminal signal sequence (20 aa), oligomerization and fusion domain and a hydrophobic transmembrane domain near the C-terminus (7 aa).
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] It is produced in both early and late phases of the infection cycle with a maximal rate of synthesis occurring in 24–26 h after infection.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Trimerization with intermolecular cysteine-bonds seems to be a crucial step for protein transport to cell surface, since only 33% of synthesized protein reaches cell surface, as monomeric gp64 is degraded within the cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Gp64 is essential for efficient budding of the virion and for the cell-to-cell transmission during the infection cycle, as well as viral entry, i.e. causing viral trophism and endosome-mediated uptake to the cell.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The major function of the gp64 envelope protein is to cause the pH-mediated envelope fusion to the endosome.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Although gp64 has variety of essential functions, it has been reported that gp64-null baculoviruses can be substituted with other viral glycoproteins such as Ld130, G-protein of *Vesicular stomatitis* virus.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] These substitutions will result in functional virons.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Baculovirus expression in insect cells represents a robust method for producing recombinant glycoproteins or membrane proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] In the early 1990s, a system was developed by Monsanto that allows for easy and fast generation of recombinant baculoviruses.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Baculovirus-produced proteins have been in use since 2007 as vaccines against human papillomavirus infection, successfully protecting against cervical cancer.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Baculovirus-produced proteins are currently under study as therapeutic cancer vaccines with several immunologic advantages over proteins derived from mammalian sources.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Members of the genus *Heliothis*—cosmopolitan insects that attack at least 30 food- and fibre-yielding crop plants—have been controlled by the application of *Baculovirus heliothis*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] In 1975, the United States Environmental Protection Agency registered the *B. heliothis* preparations.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] NPV preparations have also been used commercially against pests such as *Trichoplusia* (under the biotrol-VTN brand name) and the cotton leafworm (under the biotrol-VSE brand name).
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Baculoviruses are incapable of replicating within the cells of mammals and plants.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] They have a restricted range of hosts they can infect that is typically restricted to a limited number of closely related insect species.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Because baculoviruses are not harmful to humans, they are considered a safe option for use in research applications.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] They are also used as biological agents as in the case of the Indian mealmoth, a grain-feeding pest.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] However, in the scope of biosafety, it must be considered that baculoviruses are harmful, if not lethal to insect populations, as described above.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Therefore, their usage should preferably occur in controlled settings limiting the dissemination into the environment.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The name of this family has been derived from the Latin word *baculus*, meaning "stick".
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] The polyhedral capsid from which the virus gets its name is an extremely stable protein crystal that protects the virus in the external environment.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] It dissolves in the alkaline midgut of moths and butterflies to release the virus particle and infect the larva.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] An example of an insect that it infects is the fall webworm.
[src:protein-expression-systems/baculovirus] Baculoviruses are thought to have evolved from the *Nudiviridae* family of viruses 310 million years ago.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Some serotypes, such as EPEC and ETEC, are pathogenic, causing serious food poisoning in their hosts.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Fecal–oral transmission is the major route through which pathogenic strains of the bacterium cause disease.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] This transmission method is occasionally responsible for food contamination incidents that prompt product recalls.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Cells are able to survive outside the body for a limited amount of time, which makes them potential indicator organisms to test environmental samples for fecal contamination.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] A growing body of research, though, has examined environmentally persistent *E. coli* which can survive for many days and grow outside a host.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The bacterium can be grown and cultured easily and inexpensively in a laboratory setting, and has been intensively investigated for over 60 years.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] *E. coli* is a chemoheterotroph whose chemically defined medium must include a source of carbon and energy.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] *E. coli* is the most widely studied prokaryotic model organism, and an important species in the fields of biotechnology and microbiology, where it has served as the host organism for the majority of work with recombinant DNA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Under favourable conditions, it takes as little as 20 minutes to reproduce.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The flagella, which allow the bacteria to swim, have a peritrichous arrangement.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The flagella attach and efface to the microvilli of the intestines via an adhesion molecule known as intimin.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In addition, *E. coli*'s metabolism can be rewired to solely use CO2 as the source of carbon for biomass production.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In other words, this obligate heterotroph's metabolism can be altered to display autotrophic capabilities by heterologously expressing carbon fixation genes as well as formate dehydrogenase and conducting laboratory evolution experiments.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] This may be done by using formate to reduce electron carriers and supply the ATP required in anabolic pathways inside of these synthetic autotrophs.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] When growing in the presence of a mixture of sugars, bacteria will often consume the sugars sequentially through a process known as catabolite repression.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] By repressing the expression of the genes involved in metabolizing the less preferred sugars, cells will usually first consume the sugar yielding the highest growth rate, followed by the sugar yielding the next highest growth rate, and so on.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In doing so the cells ensure that their limited metabolic resources are being used to maximize the rate of growth.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The well-used example of this with *E. coli* involves the growth of the bacterium on glucose and lactose, where *E. coli* will consume glucose before lactose.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Catabolite repression has also been observed in *E. coli* in the presence of other non-glucose sugars, such as arabinose and xylose, sorbitol, rhamnose, and ribose.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In *E. coli*, glucose catabolite repression is regulated by the phosphotransferase system, a multi-protein phosphorylation cascade that couples glucose uptake and metabolism.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Optimum growth of *E. coli* occurs at 37 °C (99 °F), but some laboratory strains can multiply at temperatures up to 49 °C (120 °F).
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] *E. coli* grows in a variety of defined laboratory media, such as lysogeny broth, or any medium that contains glucose, ammonium phosphate monobasic, sodium chloride, magnesium sulfate, potassium phosphate dibasic, and water.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Growth can be driven by aerobic or anaerobic respiration, using a large variety of redox pairs, including the oxidation of pyruvic acid, formic acid, hydrogen, and amino acids, and the reduction of substrates such as oxygen, nitrate, fumarate, dimethyl sulfoxide, and trimethylamine N-oxide.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] *E. coli* is classified as a facultative anaerobe.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] It uses oxygen when it is present and available.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] It can, however, continue to grow in the absence of oxygen using fermentation or anaerobic respiration.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Respiration type is managed in part by the arc system.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The ability to continue growing in the absence of oxygen is an advantage to bacteria because their survival is increased in environments where water predominates.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The bacterial cell cycle is divided into three stages.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The B period occurs between the completion of cell division and the beginning of DNA replication.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The C period encompasses the time it takes to replicate the chromosomal DNA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The D period refers to the stage between the conclusion of DNA replication and the end of cell division.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The doubling rate of *E. coli* is higher when more nutrients are available.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] However, the length of the C and D periods do not change, even when the doubling time becomes less than the sum of the C and D periods.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] At the fastest growth rates, replication begins before the previous round of replication has completed, resulting in multiple replication forks along the DNA and overlapping cell cycles.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The number of replication forks in fast growing *E. coli* typically follows 2n (n = 1, 2 or 3).
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] This only happens if replication is initiated simultaneously from all origins of replications, and is referred to as synchronous replication.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] However, not all cells in a culture replicate synchronously.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In this case cells do not have multiples of two replication forks.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Replication initiation is then referred to being asynchronous.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] However, asynchrony can be caused by mutations to for instance *dnaA* or DnaA initiator-associating protein DiaA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Although *E. coli* reproduces by binary fission the two supposedly identical cells produced by cell division are functionally asymmetric with the old pole cell acting as an aging parent that repeatedly produces rejuvenated offspring.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] When exposed to an elevated stress level, damage accumulation in an old *E. coli* lineage may surpass its immortality threshold so that it arrests division and becomes mortal.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Cellular aging is a general process, affecting prokaryotes and eukaryotes alike.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In fact, from the more constructive point of view, the members of genus *Shigella* (*S. dysenteriae*, *S. flexneri*, *S. boydii*, and *S. sonnei*) should be classified as *E. coli* strains, a phenomenon termed taxa in disguise.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Similarly, other strains of *E. coli* (e.g. the K-12 strain commonly used in recombinant DNA work) are sufficiently different that they would merit reclassification.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] A strain is a subgroup within the species that has unique characteristics that distinguish it from other strains.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] These differences are often detectable only at the molecular level; however, they may result in changes to the physiology or lifecycle of the bacterium.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] For example, a strain may gain pathogenic capacity, the ability to use a unique carbon source, the ability to take upon a particular ecological niche, or the ability to resist antimicrobial agents.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Different strains of *E. coli* are often host-specific, making it possible to determine the source of fecal contamination in environmental samples.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] For example, knowing which *E. coli* strains are present in a water sample allows researchers to make assumptions about whether the contamination originated from a human, another mammal, or a bird.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] A common subdivision system of *E. coli*, but not based on evolutionary relatedness, is by serotype, which is based on major surface antigens (O antigen: part of lipopolysaccharide layer; H: flagellin; K antigen: capsule), e.g.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] It is, however, common to cite only the serogroup, i.e. the O-antigen.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] At present, about 190 serogroups are known.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Nonpathogenic strains which are commonly used in research laboratories lack an O-antigen and are thus not serotypeable.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Like all lifeforms, new strains of *E. coli* evolve through the natural biological processes of mutation, gene duplication, and horizontal gene transfer; in particular, 18% of the genome of the laboratory strain MG1655 was horizontally acquired since the divergence from *Salmonella*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] *E. coli* K-12 and *E. coli* B strains are the most frequently used varieties for laboratory purposes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Some strains develop traits that can be harmful to a host animal.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] These virulent strains typically cause a bout of diarrhea that is often self-limiting in healthy adults but is frequently lethal to children in the developing world.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] More virulent strains, such as O157:H7, cause serious illness or death in the elderly, the very young, or the immunocompromised.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The genera *Escherichia* and *Salmonella* diverged around 102 million years ago (credibility interval: 57–176 mya), an event unrelated to the much earlier (see *Synapsid*) divergence of their hosts: the former being found in mammals and the latter in birds and reptiles.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] This was followed by a split of an *Escherichia* ancestor into five species (*E. albertii*, *E. coli*, *E. fergusonii*, *E. hermannii*, and *E. vulneris*).
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The last *E. coli* ancestor split between 20 and 30 million years ago.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The long-term evolution experiments using *E. coli*, begun by Richard Lenski in 1988, have allowed direct observation of genome evolution over more than 65,000 generations in the laboratory.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] For instance, *E. coli* typically do not have the ability to grow aerobically with citrate as a carbon source, which is used as a diagnostic criterion with which to differentiate *E. coli* from other, closely, related bacteria such as *Salmonella*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In this experiment, one population of *E. coli* unexpectedly evolved the ability to aerobically metabolize citrate, a major evolutionary shift with some hallmarks of microbial speciation.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In the microbial world, a relationship of predation can be established similar to that observed in the animal world.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Considered, it has been seen that *E. coli* is the prey of multiple generalist predators, such as *Myxococcus xanthus*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In this predator-prey relationship, a parallel evolution of both species is observed through genomic and phenotypic modifications.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] However, in most studies, either O157:H7, K-12 MG1655, or K-12 W3110 were used as a representative *E. coli*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The genome of the type strain has only lately (2013) been sequenced.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Many strains belonging to this species have been isolated and characterised.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In addition to serotype (*vide supra*), they can be classified according to their phylogeny, i.e. the inferred evolutionary history, as shown below where the species is divided into six groups as of 2014.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Particularly the use of whole genome sequences yields highly supported phylogenies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The phylogroup structure remains robust to newer methods and sequences, which sometimes adds newer groups, giving 8 or 14 as of 2023.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The link between phylogenetic distance ("relatedness") and pathology is small, *e.g.* the O157:H7 serotype strains, which form a clade ("an exclusive group")—group E below—are all enterohaemorragic strains (EHEC), but not all EHEC strains are closely related.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In fact, four different species of *Shigella* are nested among *E. coli* strains (*vide supra*), while *E. albertii* and *E. fergusonii* are outside this group.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Indeed, all *Shigella* species were placed within a single subspecies of *E. coli* in a phylogenomic study that included the type strain.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] All commonly used research strains of *E. coli* belong to group A and are derived mainly from Clifton's K-12 strain (λ+ F+; O16) and to a lesser degree from d'Herelle's "Bacillus coli" strain (B strain; O7).
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] There have been multiple proposals to revise the taxonomy to match phylogeny.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] However, all these proposals need to face the fact that *Shigella* remains a widely used name in medicine and find ways to reduce any confusion that can stem from renaming.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The first complete DNA sequence of an *E. coli* genome (laboratory strain K-12 derivative MG1655) was published in 1997.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] It is a circular DNA molecule 4.6 million base pairs in length, containing 4288 annotated protein-coding genes (organized into 2584 operons), seven ribosomal RNA (rRNA) operons, and 86 transfer RNA (tRNA) genes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Despite having been the subject of intensive genetic analysis for about 40 years, many of these genes were previously unknown.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The coding density was found to be very high, with a mean distance between genes of only 118 base pairs.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The genome was observed to contain a significant number of transposable genetic elements, repeat elements, cryptic prophages, and bacteriophage remnants.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] More than three hundred complete genomic sequences of *Escherichia* and *Shigella* species are known.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The genome sequence of the type strain of *E. coli* was added to this collection before 2014.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Comparison of these sequences shows a remarkable amount of diversity; only about 20% of each genome represents sequences present in every one of the isolates, while around 80% of each genome can vary among isolates.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Each individual genome contains between 4,000 and 5,500 genes, but the total number of different genes among all of the sequenced *E. coli* strains (the pangenome) exceeds 16,000.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] This very large variety of component genes has been interpreted to mean that two-thirds of the *E. coli* pangenome originated in other species and arrived through the process of horizontal gene transfer.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Genes in *E. coli* are usually named in accordance with the uniform nomenclature proposed by Demerec et al.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Gene names are 3-letter acronyms that derive from their function (when known) or mutant phenotype and are italicized.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] When multiple genes have the same acronym, the different genes are designated by a capital later that follows the acronym and is also italicized.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] For instance, *recA* is named after its role in homologous recombination plus the letter A.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Functionally related genes are named *recB*, *recC*, *recD* etc.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The proteins are named by uppercase acronyms, e.g.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] When the genome of *E. coli* strain K-12 substr.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] MG1655 was sequenced, all known or predicted protein-coding genes were numbered (more or less) in their order on the genome and abbreviated by b numbers, such as b2819 (= *recD*).
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The "b" names were created after Fred Blattner, who led the genome sequence effort.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Another numbering system was introduced with the sequence of another *E. coli* K-12 substrain, W3110, which was sequenced in Japan and hence uses numbers starting by JW...
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Note, however, that most databases have their own numbering system, e.g. the EcoGene database uses EG10826 for *recD*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Finally, ECK numbers are specifically used for alleles in the MG1655 strain of *E. coli* K-12.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Complete lists of genes and their synonyms can be obtained from databases such as EcoGene or Uniprot.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The genome sequence of *E. coli* predicts 4288 protein-coding genes, of which 38 percent initially had no attributed function.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Comparison with five other sequenced microbes reveals ubiquitous as well as narrowly distributed gene families; many families of similar genes within *E. coli* are also evident.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The largest family of paralogous proteins contains 80 ABC transporters.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The genome as a whole is strikingly organized with respect to the local direction of replication; guanines, oligonucleotides possibly related to replication and recombination, and most genes are so oriented.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The genome also contains insertion sequence (IS) elements, phage remnants, and many other patches of unusual composition indicating genome plasticity through horizontal transfer.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Several studies have experimentally investigated the proteome of *E. coli*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] By 2006, 1,627 (38%) of the predicted proteins (open reading frames, ORFs) had been identified experimentally.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] 2020 detected 2,586 proteins with at least 2 peptides (60% of all proteins).
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Although much fewer bacterial proteins seem to have post-translational modifications (PTMs) compared to eukaryotic proteins, a substantial number of proteins are modified in *E. coli*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] (2018) found 227 phosphoproteins of which 173 were phosphorylated on histidine.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The majority of phosphorylated amino acids were serine (1,220 sites) with only 246 sites on histidine and 501 phosphorylated threonines and 162 tyrosines.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The interactome of *E. coli* has been studied by affinity purification and mass spectrometry (AP/MS) and by analyzing the binary interactions among its proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Due to the low cost and speed with which it can be grown and modified in laboratory settings, *E. coli* is a popular expression platform for the production of recombinant proteins used in therapeutics.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] One advantage to using *E. coli* over another expression platform is that *E. coli* naturally does not export many proteins into the periplasm, making it easier to recover a protein of interest without cross-contamination.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The *E. coli* K-12 strains and their derivatives (DH1, DH5α, MG1655, RV308 and W3110) are the strains most widely used by the biotechnology industry.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Nonpathogenic *E. coli* strain Nissle 1917 (EcN), (Mutaflor) and *E. coli* O83:K24:H31 (Colinfant)) are used as probiotic agents in medicine, mainly for the treatment of various gastrointestinal diseases, including inflammatory bowel disease.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] It is thought that the EcN strain might impede the growth of opportunistic pathogens, including *Salmonella* and other coliform enteropathogens, through the production of microcin proteins the production of siderophores.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Most *E. coli* strains do not cause disease, naturally living in the gut, but virulent strains can cause gastroenteritis, urinary tract infections, neonatal meningitis, hemorrhagic colitis, and Crohn's disease.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Common signs and symptoms include severe abdominal cramps, diarrhea, hemorrhagic colitis, vomiting, and sometimes fever.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In rarer cases, virulent strains are also responsible for bowel necrosis (tissue death) and perforation without progressing to hemolytic–uremic syndrome, peritonitis, mastitis, sepsis, and gram-negative pneumonia.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Very young children are more susceptible to develop severe illness, such as hemolytic uremic syndrome; however, healthy individuals of all ages are at risk to the severe consequences that may arise as a result of being infected with *E. coli*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Some strains of *E. coli*, for example O157:H7, can produce Shiga toxin.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The Shiga toxin causes inflammatory responses in target cells of the gut, leaving behind lesions which result in the bloody diarrhea that is a symptom of a Shiga toxin-producing *E. coli* (STEC) infection.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] This toxin further causes premature destruction of the red blood cells, which then clog the body's filtering system, the kidneys, in some rare cases (usually in children and the elderly) causing hemolytic-uremic syndrome (HUS), which may lead to kidney failure and even death.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Signs of hemolytic uremic syndrome include decreased frequency of urination, lethargy, and paleness of cheeks and inside the lower eyelids.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In 25% of HUS patients, complications of the nervous system occur, which in turn causes strokes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In addition, this strain causes the buildup of fluid (since the kidneys do not work), leading to edema around the lungs, legs, and arms.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] This increase in fluid buildup, especially around the lungs, impedes the functioning of the heart, causing an increase in blood pressure.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Uropathogenic *E. coli* (UPEC) is one of the main causes of urinary tract infections.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] It is part of the normal microbiota in the gut and can be introduced in many ways.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In particular for females, the direction of wiping after defecation (wiping back to front) can lead to fecal contamination of the urogenital orifices.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Anal intercourse can also introduce this bacterium into the male urethra, and in switching from anal to vaginal intercourse, the male can also introduce UPEC to the female urogenital system.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Enterotoxigenic *E. coli* (ETEC) is the most common cause of traveler's diarrhea, with as many as 840 million cases worldwide in developing countries each year.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The bacteria, typically transmitted through contaminated food or drinking water, adheres to the intestinal lining, where it secretes either of two types of enterotoxins, leading to watery diarrhea.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The rate and severity of infections are higher among children under the age of five, including as many as 380,000 deaths annually.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In May 2011, one *E. coli* strain, O104:H4, was the subject of a bacterial outbreak that began in Germany.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Certain strains of *E. coli* are a major cause of foodborne illness.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The outbreak started when several people in Germany were infected with enterohemorrhagic *E. coli* (EHEC) bacteria, leading to hemolytic-uremic syndrome (HUS), a medical emergency that requires urgent treatment.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The outbreak spread to 15 other countries, including regions in North America.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] On 30 June 2011, the German *Bundesinstitut für Risikobewertung (BfR)* (Federal Institute for Risk Assessment, a federal institute within the German Federal Ministry of Food, Agriculture and Consumer Protection) announced that seeds of fenugreek from Egypt were likely the cause of the EHEC outbreak.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Some studies have demonstrated an absence of *E. coli* in the gut flora of subjects with the metabolic disorder Phenylketonuria.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] It is hypothesized that the absence of these normal bacteria impairs the production of the key vitamins B2 (riboflavin) and K2 (menaquinone) – vitamins which are implicated in many physiological roles in humans such as cellular and bone metabolism – and so contributes to the disorder.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The time between ingesting the STEC bacteria and feeling sick is called the "incubation period".
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The incubation period is usually 3–4 days after the exposure, but may be as short as 1 day or as long as 10 days.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The symptoms often begin slowly with mild belly pain or non-bloody diarrhea that worsens over several days.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] HUS, if it occurs, develops an average 7 days after the first symptoms, when the diarrhea is improving.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Diagnosis of infectious diarrhea and identification of antimicrobial resistance is performed using a stool culture with subsequent antibiotic sensitivity testing.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] It requires a minimum of 2 days and maximum of several weeks to culture gastrointestinal pathogens.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The sensitivity (true positive) and specificity (true negative) rates for stool culture vary by pathogen, although a number of human pathogens can not be cultured.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] For culture-positive samples, antimicrobial resistance testing takes an additional 12–24 hours to perform.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Current point of care molecular diagnostic tests can identify *E. coli* and antimicrobial resistance in the identified strains much faster than culture and sensitivity testing.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Microarray-based platforms can identify specific pathogenic strains of *E. coli* and *E. coli*-specific AMR genes in two hours or less with high sensitivity and specificity, but the size of the test panel (i.e., total pathogens and antimicrobial resistance genes) is limited.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Newer metagenomics-based infectious disease diagnostic platforms are currently being developed to overcome the various limitations of culture and all currently available molecular diagnostic technologies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The mainstay of treatment is the assessment of dehydration and replacement of fluid and electrolytes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The antibiotic used depends upon susceptibility patterns in the particular geographical region.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Currently, the antibiotics of choice are fluoroquinolones or azithromycin, with an emerging role for rifaximin.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Rifaximin, a semisynthetic rifamycin derivative, is an effective and well-tolerated antibacterial for the management of adults with non-invasive traveller's diarrhea.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Rifaximin was significantly more effective than placebo and no less effective than ciprofloxacin in reducing the duration of diarrhea.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] While rifaximin is effective in patients with *E. coli*-predominant traveller's diarrhea, it appears ineffective in patients infected with inflammatory or invasive enteropathogens.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] ETEC is the type of *E. coli* that most vaccine development efforts are focused on.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Antibodies against the LT and major CFs of ETEC provide protection against LT-producing, ETEC-expressing homologous CFs.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Oral inactivated vaccines consisting of toxin antigen and whole cells, i.e. the licensed recombinant cholera B subunit (rCTB)-WC cholera vaccine Dukoral, have been developed.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] There are currently no licensed vaccines for ETEC, though several are in various stages of development.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In different trials, the rCTB-WC cholera vaccine provided high (85–100%) short-term protection.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] An oral ETEC vaccine candidate consisting of rCTB and formalin inactivated *E. coli* bacteria expressing major CFs has been shown in clinical trials to be safe, immunogenic, and effective against severe diarrhoea in American travelers but not against ETEC diarrhoea in young children in Egypt.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] A modified ETEC vaccine consisting of recombinant *E. coli* strains over-expressing the major CFs and a more LT-like hybrid toxoid called LCTBA, are undergoing clinical testing.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Other proven prevention methods for *E. coli* transmission include handwashing and improved sanitation and drinking water, as transmission occurs through fecal contamination of food and water supplies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Additionally, thoroughly cooking meat and avoiding consumption of raw, unpasteurized beverages, such as juices and milk are other proven methods for preventing *E. coli*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Lastly, cross-contamination of utensils and work spaces should be avoided when preparing food.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Because of its long history of laboratory culture and ease of manipulation, *E. coli* plays an important role in modern biological engineering and industrial microbiology.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The work of Stanley Norman Cohen and Herbert Boyer in *E. coli*, using plasmids and restriction enzymes to create recombinant DNA, became a foundation of biotechnology.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Many proteins previously thought difficult or impossible to be expressed in *E. coli* in folded form have been successfully expressed in *E. coli*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Modified *E. coli* cells have been used in vaccine development, bioremediation, production of biofuels, lighting, and production of immobilised enzymes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Strain K-12 is a mutant form of *E. coli* that over-expresses the enzyme Alkaline phosphatase (ALP).
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The mutation arises due to a defect in the gene that constantly codes for the enzyme.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] A gene that is producing a product without any inhibition is said to have constitutive activity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] This particular mutant form is used to isolate and purify the aforementioned enzyme.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Strain OP50 of *Escherichia coli* is used for maintenance of *Caenorhabditis elegans* cultures.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Strain JM109 is a mutant form of *E. coli* that is recA and endA deficient.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The strain can be utilized for blue/white screening when the cells carry the fertility factor episome.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Lack of recA decreases the possibility of unwanted restriction of the DNA of interest and lack of endA inhibit plasmid DNA decomposition.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Thus, JM109 is useful for cloning and expression systems.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In 1946, Joshua Lederberg and Edward Tatum first described the phenomenon known as bacterial conjugation using *E. coli* as a model bacterium, and it remains the primary model to study conjugation.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] *E. coli* was an integral part of the first experiments to understand phage genetics, and early researchers, such as Seymour Benzer, used *E. coli* and phage T4 to understand the topography of gene structure.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Prior to Benzer's research, it was not known whether the gene was a linear structure, or if it had a branching pattern.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Biochemistry and replication machinery were not altered.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] By evaluating the possible combination of nanotechnologies with landscape ecology, complex habitat landscapes can be generated with details at the nanoscale.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] On such synthetic ecosystems, evolutionary experiments with *E. coli* have been performed to study the spatial biophysics of adaptation in an island biogeography on-chip.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In other studies, non-pathogenic *E. coli* has been used as a model microorganism towards understanding the effects of simulated microgravity (on Earth) on the same.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Since 1961, scientists proposed the idea of genetic circuits used for computational tasks.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Collaboration between biologists and computing scientists has allowed designing digital logic gates on the metabolism of *E. coli*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] As Lac operon is a two-stage process, genetic regulation in the bacteria is used to realize computing functions.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The process is controlled at the transcription stage of DNA into messenger RNA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Studies are being performed attempting to program *E. coli* to solve complicated mathematics problems, such as the Hamiltonian path problem.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] A computer to control protein production of *E. coli* within yeast cells has been developed.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] A method has also been developed to use bacteria to behave as an LCD screen.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In July 2017, separate experiments with *E. coli* published on Nature showed the potential of using living cells for computing tasks and storing information.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] A team formed with collaborators of the Biodesign Institute at Arizona State University and Harvard's Wyss Institute for Biologically Inspired Engineering developed a biological computer inside *E. coli* that responded to a dozen inputs.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] The team called the computer "ribocomputer", as it was composed of ribonucleic acid.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Meanwhile, Harvard researchers probed that is possible to store information in bacteria after successfully archiving images and movies in the DNA of living *E. coli* cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In 2021, a team led by biophysicist Sangram Bagh realized a study with *E. coli* to solve 2 × 2 maze problems to probe the principle for distributed computing among cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In 1885, the German-Austrian pediatrician Theodor Escherich discovered this organism in the feces of healthy individuals.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] He called it *Bacterium coli commune* because it is found in the colon.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] Early classifications of prokaryotes placed these in a handful of genera based on their shape and motility (at that time Ernst Haeckel's classification of bacteria in the kingdom Monera was in place).
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In 1996, an outbreak of *E. coli* food poisoning occurred in Wishaw, Scotland, killing 21 people.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] This death toll was exceeded in 2011, when an *E. coli* O104:H4 outbreak starting in Germany, linked to organic fenugreek sprouts, killed 53 people.
[src:protein-expression-systems/escherichia-coli] In 2024, an outbreak of *E. coli* food poisoning occurred across the U.S. was linked to U.S.-grown organic carrots causing one fatality and dozens of illnesses.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Inclusion bodies in neurons may accumulate in the cytoplasm or nucleus, and are associated with many neurodegenerative diseases.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Bunina bodies in motor neurons are a core feature of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Other usual cell inclusions are often temporary inclusions of accumulated proteins, fats, secretory granules, or other insoluble components.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] A typical finding in the lung tissue of tobacco smokers are pigmented cytoplasmic granules shown in macrophages known as *smoker's inclusion bodies*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Inclusion bodies are found in bacteria as particles of aggregated protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] They have a higher density than many other cell components but are porous.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] They typically represent sites of viral multiplication in a bacterium or a eukaryotic cell and usually consist of viral capsid proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Inclusion bodies contain very little host protein, ribosomal components, or DNA/RNA fragments.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] They often almost exclusively contain the over-expressed protein and aggregation and has been reported to be reversible.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] It has been suggested that inclusion bodies are dynamic structures formed by an unbalanced equilibrium between aggregated and soluble proteins of *Escherichia coli*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] There is a growing body of information indicating that formation of inclusion bodies occurs as a result of intracellular accumulation of partially folded expressed proteins which aggregate through non-covalent hydrophobic or ionic interactions or a combination of both.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Inclusion bodies have a non-unit (single) lipid membrane.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Protein inclusion bodies are classically thought to contain misfolded protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] However, this has been contested, as green fluorescent protein will sometimes fluoresce in inclusion bodies, which indicates some resemblance of the native structure and researchers have recovered folded protein from inclusion bodies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] When genes from one organism are expressed in another organism the resulting protein sometimes forms inclusion bodies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] This is often true when large evolutionary distances are crossed: a cDNA isolated from Eukarya for example, and expressed as a recombinant gene in a prokaryote risks the formation of the inactive aggregates of protein known as inclusion bodies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] While the cDNA may properly code for a translatable mRNA, the protein that results will emerge in a foreign microenvironment.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] This often has fatal effects, especially if the intent of cloning is to produce a biologically active protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] For example, eukaryotic systems for carbohydrate modification and membrane transport are not found in prokaryotes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] The internal microenvironment of a prokaryotic cell (pH, osmolarity) may differ from that of the original source of the gene.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Mechanisms for folding a protein may also be absent, and hydrophobic residues that normally would remain buried may be exposed and available for interaction with similar exposed sites on other ectopic proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Processing systems for the cleavage and removal of internal peptides would also be absent in bacteria.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] The initial attempts to clone insulin in a bacterium suffered all of these deficits.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] In addition, the fine controls that may keep the concentration of a protein low will also be missing in a prokaryotic cell, and overexpression can result in filling a cell with ectopic protein that, even if it were properly folded, would precipitate by saturating its environment.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Inclusion bodies are aggregates of protein associated with many neurodegenerative diseases, accumulated in the cytoplasm or nucleus of neurons.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Inclusion bodies of aggregations of multiple proteins are also found in muscle cells affected by inclusion body myositis and hereditary inclusion body myopathy.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] A red blood cell (erythrocyte) does not usually have inclusions in the cytoplasm, but they may be seen in certain blood disorders.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Basophilic stipplings – these stipplings are either fine or coarse, deep blue to purple staining inclusion that appear on a dried Wright's stain.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Pappenheimer bodies – are siderotic granules which are small, irregular, dark-staining granules that appear near the periphery of a young erythrocyte in a Wright's stain.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Polychromatophilic red cells – young red blood cells that no longer have nucleus but still contain some RNA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Cabot rings – ring-like structure and may appear in red blood cells in megaloblastic anemia or in severe anemias, lead poisoning, and in dyserythropoiesis, in which erythrocytes are destroyed before being released from the bone marrow.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Hemoglobin H inclusions – alpha thalassemia, greenish-blue inclusion bodies appear in many red blood cells after four drops of blood are incubated with 0.5mL of Brilliant cresyl blue for 20 minutes at 37 °C.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Examples of viral inclusion bodies in plants include aggregations of virus particles (like those for *Cucumber mosaic virus*) and aggregations of viral proteins (like the cylindrical inclusions of potyviruses).
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Depending on the plant and the plant virus family these inclusions can be found in epidermal cells, mesophyll cells, and stomatal cells when plant tissue is properly stained.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Polyhydroxyalkanoates (PHA) are produced by bacteria as inclusion bodies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] The size of PHA granules are limited in *E. coli*, due to its small size.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Bacterial cell's inclusion bodies are not as abundant intracellularly, in comparison to eukaryotic cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Polymeric R bodies are found in the bacterial cytoplasm of some taxa, and thought to be involved in toxin delivery.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Between 70% and 80% of recombinant proteins expressed *E. coli* are contained in inclusion bodies (i.e., protein aggregates).
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] The purification of the expressed proteins from inclusion bodies usually require two main steps: extraction of inclusion bodies from the bacteria followed by the solubilisation of the purified inclusion bodies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Solubilisation of inclusions bodies often involves treatment with denaturing agents, such as urea or guanidine chloride at high concentrations, to de-aggregate the collapsed proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Renaturation follows the treatment with denaturing agents and often consists of dialysis and/or use of molecules that promote the refolding of denatured proteins (including chaotopic agents and chaperones).
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Inclusion body diseases differ from amyloid diseases in that inclusion bodies are necessarily intracellular aggregates of protein, where amyloid can be intracellular or extracellular.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Amyloid also necessitates protein polymerization where inclusion bodies do not.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Inclusion bodies are often made of denatured aggregates of inactive proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Although, the renaturation of inclusion bodies can sometimes lead to the solubilisation and the recovery of active proteins, the process is still very empirical, uncertain and of low efficiency.
[src:protein-expression-systems/inclusion-bodies] Several techniques have been developed over the years to prevent the formation of inclusion bodies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The protein manufacturing cost remains high and there is a growing demand to develop cost efficient and rapid protein purification methods.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Understanding the different protein purification methods and optimizing the downstream processing is critical to minimize production costs while maintaining the quality of acceptable standards of homogeneity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Protein purification is either *preparative* or *analytical*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Preparative purifications aim to produce a relatively large quantity of purified proteins for subsequent use.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Examples include the preparation of commercial products such as enzymes (e.g. lactase), nutritional proteins (e.g. soy protein isolate), and certain biopharmaceuticals (e.g. insulin).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Several preparative purification steps are often deployed to remove bi-products, such as host cell proteins, which pose a potential threat to the patient's health.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Analytical purification produces a relatively small amount of a protein for a variety of research or analytical purposes, including identification, quantification, and studies of the protein's structure, post-translational modifications, and function.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Each step of a protein purification scheme is monitored and takes into consideration purification levels and yield.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] A high purification level and a poor yield leaves hardly any protein with which to experiment.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] On the other hand, a high yield with low purification levels leaves many contaminants (proteins other than the one interest) which interfere with research purposes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] If the protein of interest is not secreted by the organism into the surrounding solution, the first step of each purification process is the disruption of the cells containing the protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Triton X-100) and/or enzymes (e.g. lysozyme).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Finally, the cell debris can be removed by differential centrifugation, which is a procedure where the homogenate is centrifuged at low speed, then again at a greater force to yield a pellet consisting of nuclei and supernatant.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This yields several fractions of decreasing density where more discriminating purification techniques are applied to one fraction.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Also, proteases are released during cell lysis, which will start digesting the proteins in the solution.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] If the protein of interest is sensitive to proteolysis, it is recommended to proceed quickly, and to keep the extract cooled, to slow down the digestion.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Alternatively, one or more protease inhibitors can be added to the lysis buffer immediately before cell disruption.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Sometimes it is also necessary to add DNAse in order to reduce the viscosity of the cell lysate caused by a high DNA content.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Centrifugation is a process that uses centrifugal force to separate mixtures of particles of varying masses or densities suspended in a liquid.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] When a vessel (typically a tube or bottle) containing a mixture of proteins or other particulate matter, such as bacterial cells, is rotated at high speeds, the inertia of each particle yields a force in the direction of the particles velocity that is proportional to its mass.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The tendency of a given particle to move through the liquid because of this force is offset by the resistance the liquid exerts on the particle.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The net effect of "spinning" the sample in a centrifuge is that massive, small, and dense particles move outward faster than less massive particles or particles with more "drag" in the liquid.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] When suspensions of particles are "spun" in a centrifuge, a "pellet" may form at the bottom of the vessel that is enriched for the most massive particles with low drag in the liquid.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Non-compacted particles remain mostly in the liquid called "supernatant" and can be removed from the vessel thereby separating the supernatant from the pellet.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The rate of centrifugation is determined by the angular acceleration applied to the sample, typically measured in comparison to the g-force.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] If samples are centrifuged long enough, the particles in the vessel will reach equilibrium wherein the particles accumulate specifically at a point in the vessel where their buoyant density is balanced with centrifugal force.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Such an "equilibrium" centrifugation can allow extensive purification of a given particle.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Sucrose gradient centrifugation—a linear concentration gradient of sugar (typically sucrose, glycerol, or a silica-based density gradient media, like Percoll)—is generated in a tube such that the highest concentration is on the bottom and lowest on top.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] A protein sample is then layered on top of the gradient and spun at high speeds in an ultracentrifuge.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This causes heavy macromolecules to migrate towards the bottom of the tube faster than lighter material.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] During centrifugation in the absence of sucrose, as particles move farther and farther from the center of rotation, they experience more and more centrifugal force (the further they move, the faster they move).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The problem with this is that the useful separation range within the vessel is restricted to a small observable window.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Spinning a sample twice as long does not mean the particle of interest will go twice as far; in fact, it will go significantly further.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] However, when the proteins are moving through a sucrose gradient, they encounter liquid of increasing density and viscosity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] A properly designed sucrose gradient will counteract the increasing centrifugal force so the particles move in close proportion to the time they have been in the centrifugal field.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Samples separated by these gradients are referred to as "rate zonal" centrifugations.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] After separating the protein/particles, the gradient is then fractionated and collected.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In biochemistry, ultracentrifugation is valuable for separating biomolecules and analyzing their physical properties.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The choice of starting material is key to the design of a purification process.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In a plant or animal, a particular protein usually is not distributed homogeneously throughout the body; different organs or tissues have higher or lower concentrations of the protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The use of only the tissues or organs with the highest concentration decreases the volumes needed to produce a given amount of purified protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] If the protein is present in low abundance, or if it has a high value, scientists may use recombinant DNA technology to develop cells that will produce large quantities of the desired protein (this is known as an expression system).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Recombinant expression allows the protein to be tagged, e.g. by a His-tag or Strep-tag to facilitate purification, reducing the number of purification steps required.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Analytical purification generally utilizes three properties to separate proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] First, proteins may be purified according to their isoelectric points by running them through a pH-graded gel or an ion exchange column.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Second, proteins can be separated according to their size or molecular weight via size exclusion chromatography or by SDS-PAGE (sodium dodecyl sulfate-polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis) analysis.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Proteins are often purified by using 2D-PAGE and are then analysed by peptide mass fingerprinting to establish the protein identity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This is very useful for scientific purposes and the detection limits for protein are nowadays very low and nanogram amounts of protein are sufficient for their analysis.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Thirdly, proteins may be separated by polarity/hydrophobicity via high-performance liquid chromatography or reversed-phase chromatography.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Usually, a protein purification protocol contains one or more chromatographic steps.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The basic procedure in chromatography is to flow the solution containing the protein through a column packed with various materials.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Different proteins interact differently with the column material, and can thus be separated by the time required to pass the column, or the conditions required to elute the protein from the column.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Proteins are typically detected as they are coming off the column by their absorbance at 280 nm.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Most proteins require some salt to dissolve in water, a process called salting in.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] As the salt concentration is increased, proteins can precipitate, a process called salting out which involves changing protein solubility.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] For example, in bulk protein purification, a common first step to isolate proteins is precipitation with ammonium sulfate (NH4)2SO4.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This is performed by adding increasing amounts of ammonium sulfate and collecting the different fractions of precipitated protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Subsequently, ammonium sulfate can be removed using dialysis (separating proteins from small molecules through a semipermeable membrane).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] During the ammonium sulfate precipitation step, hydrophobic groups present on the proteins are exposed to the atmosphere, attracting other hydrophobic groups; the result is the formation of an aggregate of hydrophobic components.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In this case, the protein precipitate will typically be visible to the naked eye.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] One advantage of this method is that it can be performed inexpensively, even with very large volumes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The first proteins to be purified are water-soluble proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Purification of integral membrane proteins requires disruption of the cell membrane in order to isolate any one particular protein from others that are in the same membrane compartment.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Sometimes a particular membrane fraction can be isolated first, such as isolating mitochondria from cells before purifying a protein located in a mitochondrial membrane.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Chromatography can be used to separate protein in solution or denaturing conditions by using porous gels.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This technique is a more discriminating separation and is known as size exclusion chromatography.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The principle is that smaller molecules have to traverse a larger volume in a porous matrix.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Consequentially, proteins of a certain range in size will require a variable volume of eluent (solvent) before being collected at the other end of the column of gel.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Larger molecules (or proteins) will travel through less volume and elute prior to smaller molecules.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In the context of protein purification, the eluent is usually pooled in different test tubes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] All test tubes containing no measurable trace of the protein to purify are discarded.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The remaining solution is thus made of the protein to purify and any other similarly-sized proteins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] One chromatography technique based on molecular properties is usually not sufficient in obtaining a protein of high purity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In addition to size, ion exchange chromatography separates compounds according to the nature and degree of their ionic charge.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The column to be used is selected according to its type and strength of charge.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Anion exchange resins have a positive charge and are used to retain and separate negatively charged compounds (anions), while cation exchange resins have a negative charge and are used to separate positively charged molecules (cations).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Before the separation begins a buffer is pumped through the column to equilibrate the opposing charged ions.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Upon injection of the sample, solute molecules will exchange with the buffer ions as each competes for the binding sites on the resin.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The length of retention for each solute depends upon the strength of its charge.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The most weakly charged compounds will elute first, followed by those with successively stronger charges.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Because of the nature of the separating mechanism, pH, buffer type, buffer concentration, and temperature all play important roles in controlling the separation.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Ion exchange chromatography is a very powerful tool for use in protein purification and is frequently used in both analytical and preparative separations.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] It is especially useful when purifying nucleic-acid binding proteins, where separation of the protein from the bound nucleic acid is required to obtain a pure sample devoid of nucleic acids co-purified from the expression system or the native source.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Free-flow electrophoresis (FFE) is a carrier-free electrophoresis technique that allows preparative protein separation in a laminar buffer stream by using an orthogonal electric field.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] By making use of a pH-gradient, that can for example be induced by ampholytes, this technique allows to separate protein isoforms up to a resolution of < 0.02 delta-pI.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] HIC media is amphiphilic, with both hydrophobic and hydrophilic regions, allowing for the separation of proteins based on their surface hydrophobicity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Target proteins and their product aggregate species tend to have different hydrophobic properties and removing them via HIC further purifies the protein of interest.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Additionally, the environment used typically employs less harsh denaturing conditions than other chromatography techniques, thus helping to preserve the protein of interest in its native and functional state.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In pure water, the interactions between the resin and the hydrophobic regions of protein would be very weak, but this interaction is enhanced by applying a protein sample to HIC resin in a high ionic strength buffer.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The ionic strength of the buffer is then reduced to elute proteins in order of decreasing hydrophobicity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Affinity Chromatography is another powerful separation technique that is highly selective for the protein of interest based upon molecular conformation, which frequently utilizes application specific resins.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] These resins have ligands attached to their surfaces which are specific for the compounds to be separated.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Most frequently, these ligands function in a fashion similar to that of antibody-antigen interactions.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This "lock and key" fit between the ligand and its target compound makes it highly specific, frequently generating a single peak, while all else in the sample is unretained.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Many membrane proteins are glycoproteins and can be purified by lectin affinity chromatography.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Detergent-solubilized proteins can be allowed to bind to a chromatography resin that has been modified to have a covalently attached lectin.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Proteins that do not bind to the lectin are washed away and then specifically bound glycoproteins can be eluted by adding a high concentration of a sugar that competes with the bound glycoproteins at the lectin binding site.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Some lectins have high affinity binding to oligosaccharides of glycoproteins that is hard to compete with sugars, and bound glycoproteins need to be released by denaturing the lectin.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Immunoaffinity chromatography uses the specific binding of an antibody-antigen to selectively purify the target protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The procedure involves immobilizing a protein to a solid substrate (e.g. a porous bead or a membrane), which then selectively binds the target, while everything else flows through.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The target protein can be eluted by changing the pH or the salinity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The immobilized ligand can be an antibody (such as immunoglobulin G) or it can be a protein (such as protein A).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Because this method does not involve engineering in a tag, it can be used for proteins from natural sources.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] High-performance liquid chromatography or high-pressure liquid chromatography is a form of chromatography applying high pressure to drive the solutes through the column faster.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This means that the diffusion is limited and the resolution is improved.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The most common form is "reversed phase" HPLC, where the column material is hydrophobic.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The proteins are eluted by a gradient of increasing amounts of an organic solvent, such as acetonitrile.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The proteins elute according to their hydrophobicity.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] After purification by HPLC the protein is in a solution that only contains volatile compounds, and can easily be lyophilized.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] HPLC purification frequently results in denaturation of the purified proteins and is thus not applicable to proteins that do not spontaneously refold.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Another way to tag proteins is to engineer an antigen peptide tag onto the protein, and then purify the protein on a column or by incubating with a loose resin that is coated with an immobilized antibody.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This particular procedure is known as immunoprecipitation.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Immunoprecipitation is capable of generating an extremely specific interaction which usually results in binding only the desired protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The purified tagged proteins can then easily be separated from the other proteins in solution and later eluted back into clean solution.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] When the tags are not needed anymore, they can be cleaved off by a protease.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This often involves engineering a protease cleavage site between the tag and the protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Self-cleaving tags eliminate the need for proteases to separate tag from target protein of interest during purification process (*e.g.* *i*CapTag™).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The main component of the tag is an intein, which cleaves off simply after a pH change.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Tagless and pure target protein is then released into the elution buffer.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Emerging methods in synthetic biology explore chromatography-free alternatives by harnessing liquid-liquid phase separation to create synthetic organelles within bacterial cells, such as E. coli.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] These approaches use phase-separated RNA structures to compartmentalize proteins, enabling in-cell organization, self-cleavage via inteins, and direct release of tag-free proteins, which leads to enhanced efficiency in recombinant protein workflows.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] At the end of a protein purification, the protein often has to be concentrated.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] If the solution doesn't contain any other soluble component than the protein in question the protein can be lyophilized (dried).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This is commonly done after an HPLC run.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This simply removes all volatile components, leaving the proteins behind.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Ultrafiltration concentrates a protein solution using selective permeable membranes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The function of the membrane is to let the water and small molecules pass through while retaining the protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The solution is forced against the membrane by mechanical pump, gas pressure, or centrifugation.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The most general method to monitor the purification process is by running a SDS-PAGE of the different steps.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This method only gives a rough measure of the amounts of different proteins in the mixture, and it is not able to distinguish between proteins with similar apparent molecular weight.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] If the protein has a distinguishing spectroscopic feature or an enzymatic activity, this property can be used to detect and quantify the specific protein, and thus to select the fractions of the separation, that contains the protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] If antibodies against the protein are available then western blotting and ELISA can specifically detect and quantify the amount of desired protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Some proteins function as receptors and can be detected during purification steps by a ligand binding assay, often using a radioactive ligand.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In order to evaluate the process of multistep purification, the amount of the specific protein has to be compared to the amount of total protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The latter can be determined by the Bradford total protein assay or by absorbance of light at 280 nm, however some reagents used during the purification process may interfere with the quantification.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] For example, imidazole (commonly used for purification of polyhistidine-tagged recombinant proteins) is an amino acid analogue and at low concentrations will interfere with the bicinchoninic acid (BCA) assay for total protein quantification.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Impurities in low-grade imidazole will also absorb at 280 nm, resulting in an inaccurate reading of protein concentration from UV absorbance.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Another method to be considered is surface plasmon resonance (SPR).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] SPR can detect binding of label free molecules on the surface of a chip.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] If the desired protein is an antibody, binding can be translated directly to the activity of the protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] One can express the active concentration of the protein as the percent of the total protein.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] SPR can be a powerful method for quickly determining protein activity and overall yield.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] It is a powerful technology that requires an instrument to perform.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Gel electrophoresis is a common laboratory technique that can be used both as a preparative and analytical method.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The principle of electrophoresis relies on the movement of a charged ion in an electric field.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In practice, the proteins are denatured in a solution containing a detergent (SDS).
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In these conditions, the proteins are unfolded and coated with negatively charged detergent molecules.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The proteins in SDS-PAGE are separated on the sole basis of their size.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In analytical methods, the protein migrate as bands based on size.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Each band can be detected using stains such as Coomassie blue dye or silver stain.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] Preparative methods to purify large amounts of protein, require the extraction of the protein from the electrophoretic gel.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] This extraction may involve excision of the gel containing a band, or eluting the band directly off the gel as it runs off the end of the gel.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] In the context of a purification strategy, denaturing condition electrophoresis provides an improved resolution over size exclusion chromatography, but does not scale to large quantity of proteins in a sample as well as the late chromatography columns.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] A non-denaturing electrophoretic procedure for isolating bioactive metalloproteins in complex protein mixtures is preparative native PAGE.
[src:protein-expression-systems/protein-purification] The intactness or the structural integrity of the isolated protein must be confirmed by an independent method.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant DNA is the general name for a piece of DNA that has been created by combining two or more fragments from different sources.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant DNA is possible because DNA molecules from all organisms share the same chemical structure, differing only in the nucleotide sequence.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant DNA molecules are sometimes called **chimeric DNA** because they can be made of material from two different species like the mythical chimera. rDNA technology uses palindromic sequences and leads to the production of sticky and blunt ends.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The DNA sequences used in the construction of recombinant DNA molecules can originate from any species.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] For example, plant DNA can be joined to bacterial DNA, or human DNA can be joined with fungal DNA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] In addition, DNA sequences that do not occur anywhere in nature can be created by the chemical synthesis of DNA and incorporated into recombinant DNA molecules.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Using recombinant DNA technology and synthetic DNA, any DNA sequence can be created and introduced into living organisms.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Proteins that can result from the expression of recombinant DNA within living cells are termed *recombinant proteins*.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] When recombinant DNA encoding a protein is introduced into a host organism, the recombinant protein is not necessarily produced.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Expression of foreign proteins requires the use of specialized expression vectors and often necessitates significant restructuring by foreign coding sequences.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant DNA differs from genetic recombination in that the former results from artificial methods while the latter is a normal biological process that results in the remixing of existing DNA sequences in essentially all organisms.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Molecular cloning is the laboratory process used to produce recombinant DNA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] It is one of two most widely used methods, along with polymerase chain reaction (PCR), used to direct the replication of any specific DNA sequence chosen by the experimentalist.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] There are two fundamental differences between the methods.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] One is that molecular cloning involves replication of the DNA within a living cell, while PCR replicates DNA in the test tube, free of living cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The other difference is that cloning involves cutting and pasting DNA sequences, while PCR amplifies by copying an existing sequence.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Formation of recombinant DNA requires a cloning vector, a DNA molecule that replicates within a living cell.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The choice of vector for molecular cloning depends on the choice of host organism, the size of the DNA to be cloned, and whether and how the foreign DNA is to be expressed.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The DNA segments can be combined by using a variety of methods, such as restriction enzyme/ligase cloning or Gibson assembly.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] DNA expression requires the transfection of suitable host cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Typically, either bacterial, yeast, insect, or mammalian cells (such as human embryonic kidney cells or Chinese hamster ovary cells) are used as host cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Following transplantation into the host organism, the foreign DNA contained within the recombinant DNA construct may or may not be expressed.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] That is, the DNA may simply be replicated without expression, or it may be transcribed and translated and a recombinant protein is produced.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Generally speaking, expression of a foreign gene requires restructuring the gene to include sequences that are required for producing an mRNA molecule that can be used by the host's translational apparatus (e.g. promoter, translational initiation signal, and transcriptional terminator).
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Specific changes to the host organism may be made to improve expression of the ectopic gene.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] In addition, changes may be needed to the coding sequences as well, to optimize translation, make the protein soluble, direct the recombinant protein to the proper cellular or extracellular location, and stabilize the protein from degradation.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] In most cases, organisms containing recombinant DNA have apparently normal phenotypes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] That is, their appearance, behavior and metabolism are usually unchanged, and the only way to demonstrate the presence of recombinant sequences is to examine the DNA itself, typically using a polymerase chain reaction (PCR) test.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Significant exceptions exist, and are discussed below.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] If the rDNA sequences encode a gene that is expressed, then the presence of RNA and/or protein products of the recombinant gene can be detected, typically using RT-PCR or western hybridization methods.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Gross phenotypic changes are not the norm, unless the recombinant gene has been chosen and modified so as to generate biological activity in the host organism.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Additional phenotypes that are encountered include toxicity to the host organism induced by the recombinant gene product, especially if it is over-expressed or expressed within inappropriate cells or tissues.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] In some cases, recombinant DNA can have deleterious effects even if it is not expressed.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] One mechanism by which this happens is insertional inactivation, in which the rDNA becomes inserted into a host cell's gene.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] In some cases, researchers use this phenomenon to "knock out" genes to determine their biological function and importance.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Another mechanism by which rDNA insertion into chromosomal DNA can affect gene expression is by inappropriate activation of previously unexpressed host cell genes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] This can happen, for example, when a recombinant DNA fragment containing an active promoter becomes located next to a previously silent host cell gene, or when a host cell gene that functions to restrain gene expression undergoes insertional inactivation by recombinant DNA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant DNA is widely used in biotechnology, medicine and research.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Today, recombinant proteins and other products that result from the use of DNA technology are found in essentially every pharmacy, physician or veterinarian office, medical testing laboratory, and biological research laboratory.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The most common application of recombinant DNA is in basic research, in which the technology is important to most current work in the biological and biomedical sciences.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant DNA is used to identify, map and sequence genes, and to determine their function. rDNA probes are employed in analyzing gene expression within individual cells, and throughout the tissues of whole organisms.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant proteins are widely used as reagents in laboratory experiments and to generate antibody probes for examining protein synthesis within cells and organisms.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Many additional practical applications of recombinant DNA are found in industry, food production, human and veterinary medicine, agriculture, and bioengineering.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Some specific examples are identified below.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Found in rennet, chymosin is the enzyme responsible for hydrolysis of *κ*-casein to produce para-*κ*-casein and glycomacropeptide, which is the first step in formation of cheese, and subsequently curd, and whey.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] It was the first genetically engineered food additive used commercially.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Traditionally, processors obtained chymosin from rennet, a preparation derived from the fourth stomach of milk-fed calves.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Scientists engineered a non-pathogenic strain (K-12) of *E. coli* bacteria for large-scale laboratory production of the enzyme.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] This microbiologically produced recombinant enzyme, identical structurally to the calf derived enzyme, costs less and is produced in abundant quantities.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Today about 60% of U.S. hard cheese is made with genetically engineered chymosin.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] In 1990, FDA granted chymosin "generally recognized as safe" (GRAS) status based on data showing that the enzyme was safe.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant human insulin has almost completely replaced insulin obtained from animal sources (e.g. pigs and cattle) for the treatment of type 1 diabetes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] A variety of different recombinant insulin preparations are in widespread use.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant insulin (insulin aspart) is synthesized by inserting the human insulin gene into *E. coli* or yeast (*Saccharomyces cerevisiae*), which then produces insulin for human use.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Insulin produced by *E. coli* requires further post translational modifications (e.g. glycosylation) whereas yeasts are able to perform these modifications themselves by virtue of being more complex host organisms.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The advantage of recombinant human insulin is after chronic use patients do not develop an immune defence against it the way animal-sourced insulin stimulates the human immune system.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Human growth hormone is administered to patients whose pituitary glands generate insufficient quantities to support normal growth and development.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Before recombinant HGH became available, HGH for therapeutic use was obtained from pituitary glands of cadavers.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] This unsafe practice led to some patients developing Creutzfeldt–Jakob disease.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant HGH eliminated this problem, and is now used therapeutically.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] It has also been misused as a performance-enhancing drug by athletes and others.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Factor VIII is a blood-clotting protein that is administered to patients with the bleeding disorder hemophilia, who are unable to produce factor VIII in quantities sufficient to support normal blood coagulation.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Before the development of recombinant factor VIII, the protein was obtained by processing large quantities of human blood from multiple donors, which carried a very high risk of transmission of blood borne infectious diseases, for example HIV and hepatitis B.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Hepatitis B infection can be successfully controlled through the use of a recombinant subunit hepatitis B vaccine, which contains a form of the hepatitis B virus surface antigen that is produced in yeast cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The development of the recombinant subunit vaccine was an important and necessary development because hepatitis B virus, unlike other common viruses such as polio virus, cannot be grown in vitro.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Recombinant antibodies (rAbs) are produced in vitro by the means of expression systems based on mammalian cells.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Their monospecific binding to a specific epitope makes rAbs eligible not only for research purposes, but also as therapy options against certain cancer types, infections and autoimmune diseases.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Each of the three widely used methods for diagnosing HIV infection has been developed using recombinant DNA.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The antibody test (ELISA or western blot) uses a recombinant HIV protein to test for the presence of antibodies that the body has produced in response to an HIV infection.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The DNA test looks for the presence of HIV genetic material using reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR).
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Development of the RT-PCR test was made possible by the molecular cloning and sequence analysis of HIV genomes.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Golden rice is a recombinant variety of rice that has been engineered to express the enzymes responsible for β-carotene biosynthesis.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] This variety of rice holds substantial promise for reducing the incidence of vitamin A deficiency in the world's population.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Golden rice is not currently in use, pending the resolution of regulatory and intellectual property issues.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] These crops are in common commercial use in several countries.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The idea of recombinant DNA was first proposed by Peter Lobban, a graduate student of Prof.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Dale Kaiser in the Biochemistry Department at Stanford University Medical School.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The first publications describing the successful production and intracellular replication of recombinant DNA appeared in 1972 and 1973, from Stanford and UCSF.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] In 1980 Paul Berg, a professor in the Biochemistry Department at Stanford and an author on one of the first papers was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his work on nucleic acids "with particular regard to recombinant DNA".
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Werner Arber, Hamilton Smith, and Daniel Nathans shared the 1978 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for the discovery of restriction endonucleases which enhanced the techniques of rDNA technology.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Stanford University applied for a U.S. patent on recombinant DNA on November 4, 1974, listing the inventors as Herbert W.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Boyer (professor at the University of California, San Francisco) and Stanley N.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Cohen (professor at Stanford University); this patent, U.S.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The first licensed drug generated using recombinant DNA technology was human insulin, developed by Genentech and licensed by Eli Lilly and Company.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Scientists associated with the initial development of recombinant DNA methods recognized that the potential existed for organisms containing recombinant DNA to have undesirable or dangerous properties.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] At the 1975 Asilomar Conference on Recombinant DNA, these concerns were discussed and a voluntary moratorium on recombinant DNA research was initiated for experiments that were considered particularly risky.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] This moratorium was widely observed until the US National Institutes of Health developed and issued formal guidelines for rDNA work.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Today, recombinant DNA molecules and recombinant proteins are usually not regarded as dangerous.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] However, concerns remain about some organisms that express recombinant DNA, particularly when they leave the laboratory and are introduced into the environment or food chain.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] These concerns are discussed in the articles on genetically modified organisms and genetically modified food controversies.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] Furthermore, there are concerns about the by-products in biopharmaceutical production, where recombinant DNA result in specific protein products.
[src:protein-expression-systems/recombinant-dna] The major by-product, termed host cell protein, comes from the host expression system and poses a threat to the patient's health and the overall environment.
